# Working-tree safety

- Do not start a write task when unrelated uncommitted changes already exist.
- Report all pre-existing modified, deleted, renamed, and untracked files.
- Do not overwrite, discard, stash, revert, or absorb pre-existing changes.
- Work on a dedicated task branch unless the user explicitly authorizes direct work
  on the current branch.
- Stage only explicitly authorized paths.
- Do not run `git add .`, `git add -A`, or `git add --renormalize .`.
- Adding or changing `.gitattributes` must not cause unrelated tracked files to change.
- Before every commit, show:
  - git diff --name-status
  - git diff --cached --name-status
  - git diff --check

# Destructive Git operations

Never run without explicit user authorization:

- git reset --hard
- git clean -f, -fd, -fdx
- git checkout -- <path>
- git restore <path>
- git restore --staged combined with content deletion
- git rebase
- git commit --amend
- git push --force or --force-with-lease
- branch or tag deletion
- history rewriting
- repository reinitialization
- deletion or replacement of .git
- restoration over the active workspace from a historical copy

Never modify hashes or manifests merely to make regression pass.

